{{See also|Electric rickshaw|Electric motorcycles and scooters}}
An '''electric trike''' is a [[Three-wheeler|three-wheeled vehicle]] powered by an [[electric motor]].
[[File:TRIPL.jpg|A TRIPL used for delivery service|thumb|right]]
==Overview==
{{Importance-section|date=April 2011}}

===Definition===
{{Main|Legal definition of motorcycle}}

While the normal [[legal definition of motorcycle]] is a two-wheeled vehicle, in the USA a motorcycle may also be three-wheeled.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=72Vmfd-q5v8C&pg=PA75&dq=three-wheeled+vehicle+classified+as+a+motorcycle&hl=en&ei=wVebTc6sGIqdOt3g5PsG&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7&ved=0CFYQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Future drive: electric vehicles and sustainable transportation |author=Daniel Sperling|page=75 |publisher=Island Press, 1995 |accessdate=5 April 2011}}</ref> This classification does not depend on whether the operator is fully enclosed by a "cage" or exposed to the elements.{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}

===Configurations===
{{Main|Three-wheeler#Configurations}}

Three-wheeled vehicles with one front wheel and two rear wheels are known as a delta design or the traditional trike (tricycle) design, such as the Hase Kettwiesel.

Three-wheeled vehicles with two front wheels and one rear wheel are known as a tadpole design, such as the Odyssey Mk. 5 and Outrider 422 Alpha. Another example of an electric three-wheeled vehicle in this configuration is the [[Azkarra]], produced by Canadian company [[Girfalco]].

==Electric assisted velomobiles==
{{Main|Velomobile#Electric assisted velomobiles}}

Some three-wheeled electric vehicles, such as the [[Twike]] and the [[Myers Motors NmG]], enclose the rider in a cabin or cockpit.<ref>[http://enclosedscooter.com/category/production/ Enclosed tricycles] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101209043925/http://enclosedscooter.com/category/production/ |date=9 December 2010 }}</ref>

