The '''Mercedes-Benz C-Class''' is a line of [[compact executive car]]s produced by [[Daimler AG]]. Introduced in 1993 as a replacement for the [[Mercedes-Benz W201|190 (W201)]] range, the C-Class was the smallest model in the marque's line-up until the [[Mercedes-Benz A-Class#W168|W168 A-Class]] arrived in 1997. The C-Class is built at Mercedes-Benz factories in [[Sindelfingen]] and [[Bremen (city)|Bremen]], Germany as well as numerous satellite factories in other countries. The first C-Class (W202) sedan was produced on 1 June 1993, and the first of the second generation (W203) rolled off the assembly line on 18 July 2000. The C-Class has been available with a [[4Matic]] (i.e. [[four-wheel drive]]) option since 2002. The third generation (W204) was launched in 2007. The latest generation C-Class (W205) came out in 2014.

Though originally available as a sedan and a station wagon, the W203 series in 2000 debuted a fastback coupé (SportCoupé) version that, when facelifted, became the [[Mercedes-Benz CLC-Class]]. The CLC-Class remained in production until 2011 when it was replaced by a new W204 C-Class coupé for the 2012 model year.

== {{anchor|W202|S202}} W202 (1993–2000) ==
{{Infobox automobile
| name = W202
| image = 1998 Mercedes-Benz C 200 (W 202) Classic sedan (2010-07-05) 01.jpg
| production=May 1993–2000
| body_style = 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]]<br />5-door [[station wagon|wagon]]
}}

{{main|Mercedes-Benz C-Class (W202)}}

[[File:1994 Mercedes-Benz C 220 (W 202) Elegance sedan (2015-11-13) 02.jpg|thumbnail|left|Pre-facelift Mercedes-Benz C 220 sedan]]

In October 1986, three years into [[Mercedes-Benz W201]] (190)'s production run, work began on a successor. Design work began in 1987, with the final design by [[Murat Günak]] being selected in 1989 and the production design by [[Olivier Boulay]] delayed in January 1990, finally being patented on 19 December 1990.<ref name="google.com">{{cite web |url=http://www.google.com/patents?id=rh4nAAAAEBAJ&pg=PA6&dq=%22bruno+sacco%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=cnyzT_PvJIeq2QXN2OzpCA&ved=0CFMQ6AEwCTiCAQ#v=onepage&q=%22bruno%20sacco%22&f=false |title=Patent USD346570 – Automobile |publisher=Google}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://register.dpma.de/DPMAregister/gsm/register?GSNR=M9008365-0001 |title=DPMAregister – Designs – Registerauskunft zum Design |work=dpma.de |accessdate=24 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mercedes-benz-blog.blogspot.com/2008/07/mercedes-benz-blog-triviameeting-point.html |title=Mercedes-Benz-Blog TRIVIA: Meeting point Mercedes – 25 years of the C-Class |author=Adrian-Liviu Dorofte |work=mercedes-benz-blog.blogspot.com}}</ref><ref>europe.autonews.com/article/19970303/ANE/703030836/a-class-sets-new-record-for-mercedes</ref> Rough prototypes went into testing in 1989, with first production design prototypes commencing testing in 1990. In May 1993, the first generation [[W202]] C-Class was introduced as a replacement for the 190. The C-Class sedan was the company's entry-level model up until 1997, when Mercedes launched the A-Class. Styling themes were carried over from the previous W201 series, but the new series had a smoother and rounder design than the previous generation of compact Mercedes, with styling cues from the W124 E-Class (short, high trunk and taller tail lights), W140 S-Class (front end), and R129 SL-Class (headlights).

During the {{F1|1996}} and {{F1|1997}} [[Formula 1]] seasons, the C36 AMG served as the sport's [[Safety Car#Formula One|Safety Car]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.motorsport-total.com/f1/news/2015/03/mercedes-amg-gt-s-bernd-maylaenders-neues-safety-car-15030912.html |title=Mercedes-AMG GT S: Bernd Mayländers neues Safety-Car |date=9 March 2015 |accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref>
{{clear}}

== {{anchor|W203|S203|CL203}} W203 (2000–2007) ==
{{Infobox automobile
| name = W203
| image = 2004 Mercedes-Benz C 200 Kompressor (W 203) Elegance sedan (2011-12-06).jpg
| production = July 2000 – December 2006
| body_style = 2-door [[coupe]]<br />4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]]<br />5-door [[station wagon]]
}}

{{main|Mercedes-Benz C-Class (W203)}}

[[File:2002 Mercedes-Benz C 180 Kompressor (W 203 MY03) Elegance sedan (2015-07-09) 03.jpg|thumb|left|Pre-facelift Mercedes-Benz C 180 K sedan]]

In 1994, development began on the W203 C-Class. Design work commenced in mid-1994, with the final design being approved in December 1995 by the executive board.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oocities.org/motorcity/speedway/5350/w203design.htm |title=W203 C-Class Design Studies |publisher=oocities.org}}</ref> Design patents were filed on 20 April 1998 and 4 March 1999.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.google.com/patents/USD433653?dq=%22peter+pfeiffer%22&ei=0YWzT5C4DImA2gWYt8jpCA |title=Patent USD433653 – Exterior surface configuration of a motor vehicle |publisher=Google}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://register.dpma.de/DPMAregister/gsm/register?GSNR=49902291-0001 |title=DPMAregister – Designs – Registerauskunft zum Design |work=dpma.de |accessdate=24 January 2015}}</ref> Testing began in 1997, with development concluding in 2000. The second generation C-Class was introduced in March 2000. The sedan debuted with a range of inline-four and V6 petrol engines and inline-four and -five diesels, later W203's received the V6 diesel. Most of the engines were carried over from the W202, but the C320 was exclusive, offering {{convert|160|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}. The diesels now featured [[common rail]] [[direct fuel injection]] and [[variable geometry turbocharger]]s. A six-speed manual gearbox was optional on some of the range, With exception to the C320 and C32 AMG.   
Notably (post 2005), for the first time, the number designations were no longer equivalent to the engine displacement, more specifically in the Mercedes C200 (1.8-litre), C240 (2.6-litre) and C200 CDI (2.2-litre).
{{clear}}

== {{anchor|W204|S204|C204}} W204 (2007–2014) ==
{{Infobox automobile
| name = W204
| image =  Mercedes Benz C 180 CGi 2013 (11410856014).jpg
| production = 2007–2014
| body_style = 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]]<br />5-door [[station wagon]]<br />2-door [[coupe]]
}}

{{main|Mercedes-Benz C-Class (W204)}}

[[File:2010 Mercedes-Benz C 200 CGI (W 204) Classic sedan (2010-09-23) 02.jpg|thumbnail|left|Pre-facelift Mercedes-Benz C 200 CGI sedan]]

[[DaimlerChrysler]] introduced the W204 C-Class on 18 January 2007<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.daimlerchrysler.com/dccom/0-5-693758-1-693744-1-0-0-0-0-0-13-7163-0-0-0-0-0-0-0.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-30 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227134337/http://www.daimlerchrysler.com/dccom/0-5-693758-1-693744-1-0-0-0-0-0-13-7163-0-0-0-0-0-0-0.html |archivedate=27 December 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and displayed it in the 2007 [[Geneva Auto Show]]. Sales started on 31 March 2007 in almost all European countries. The new family had an extended wheelbase and tracks, a stiffer bodyshell and a design inspired by the [[Mercedes-Benz W221|W221 S-Class]] with some influences from the [[Mercedes-Benz CLS-Class (W219)|C219 CLS-Class]]. The C-Class received a facelift in 2011 for the 2012 model year including new LED taillights, a revised dashboard and instrument cluster layout, and a revised front fascia and headlights. The W204 platform continued into 2015 with the C-Class coupe.
{{clear}}

== {{anchor|W205|S204|C205|A205}} W205 (2014–present) ==
{{Infobox automobile
| name = W205
| image = Mercedes-Benz C 220 BlueTEC Exclusive (W 205) – Frontansicht, 12. Juli 2014, Düsseldorf.jpg
| production = 4 February 2014–present
| body_style = 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]]<br />5-door [[station wagon]]<br />2-door [[cabriolet]] / [[coupe]]
}}
{{main|Mercedes-Benz C-Class (W205)}}

[[File:2016 Mercedes-Benz C 250 (W 205) sedan (2018-08-27) 02.jpg|thumbnail|left|Mercedes-Benz C 250 sedan]]
The current generation [[Mercedes-Benz C-Class (W205)|W205 C-class]] was launched at the 2014 Detroit Auto Show. It is the first car to use the all-new Modular Rear Architecture (MRA) platform. The new structure is significantly lighter using aluminium and high strength steel extensively throughout the body, resulting in a {{convert|220|lb|kg|order=flip|adj=on}} weight decrease.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://reviews.cnet.com/sedan/2015-mercedes-benz-c/4505-10865_7-35834131.html |title=2015 Mercedes-Benz C-class review |author=Wayne Cunningham |date=24 November 2014 |publisher=CNET |accessdate=24 January 2015}}</ref>

The car was officially unveiled on 16 December 2013.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://media.daimler.com/marsMediaSite/en/instance/ko/The-new-Mercedes-Benz-C-Class-C-Class-at-its-best.xhtml?oid=9904315|title=The new Mercedes-Benz C-Class: C-Class at its best|date=13 January 2014|publisher=Daimler AG}}</ref> W205 production commenced on 4 February 2014 at the Bremen plant.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://media.daimler.com/dcmedia/0-921-656492-1-1670247-1-0-0-0-0-0-0-1549054-0-1-0-0-0-0-0.html |title=Four continents. One passion.' – Production of the New C-Class Starts at the Mercedes-Benz Bremen Plant |date=7 February 2014 |publisher=Daimler |accessdate=24 January 2016}}</ref> Production also occurs at Mercedes-Benz plants in East London, South Africa, Brazil and Tuscaloosa, Alabama, US. European sales began in March 2014, while the vehicle went on sale in North America in September 2014.

The Mercedes-Benz C-Class 205 chassis spawned four C-Class bodystyles; Sedan (W205), Wagon (S205), Coupe (C205), and Cabriolet (A205).

The W205 Mercedes-Benz C-Class received a facelift which made its debut at the 2018 Geneva Motor Show, including exterior changes and new engines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://paultan.org/2018/03/07/w205-mercedes-benz-c-class-facelift-more-details-revealed/|title=W205 Mercedes-Benz C-Class facelift – more details revealed; 1.5L turbo with mild hybrid for new C200!|author=Gerard Lye|date=7 March 2018|website=paultan.org}}</ref>

