{{Use British English|date=May 2015}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}} {{Infobox film | name = They Planted a Stone | image = | caption = | director = Robin Carruthers | producer = [[James Carr (producer)|James Carr]] | writer = Robin Carruthers | narrator = | music = | cinematography = | editing = | studio = [[Central Office of Information]] | distributor = | released = {{film date|df=yes|1953}} | runtime = 26 minutes | country = United Kingdom | language = English }} '''''They Planted a Stone''''' is a 1953 British short [[documentary film]] directed by [[Robin Carruthers]] and produced by [[James Carr (producer)|James Carr]]. It was nominated for an [[Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Documentary (Short Subject)|Best Documentary Short]].<ref name="Oscars1954">{{Cite web| url= http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1954| title= The 26th Academy Awards (1954) Nominees and Winners| accessdate= 20 August 2011| work= oscars.org| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110706093858/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/26th-winners.html| archivedate= 6 July 2011| deadurl= no| df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="NY Times">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/300247/They-Planted-A-Stone/details |title=NY Times: They Planted a Stone |accessdate=25 November 2008|work=NY Times}}</ref>
==Synopsis== The film portrays how dams, barrages and irrigation canals were constructed on the [[Nile]] in [[Sudan]], to generate [[hydroelectricity]], irrigate the desert and create such projects as the [[Gezira Scheme]].<ref name="colonial">{{cite web|url=http://www.colonialfilm.org.uk/node/1022|title=THEY PLANTED A STONE|work=Colonial Film|accessdate=8 August 2014}}</ref>
